text:
The MBA is a lot of new
things, especially for me.
There was a lot of--

I didn't know much about
business coming in,

so I felt the world was probably
a lot bigger than what I knew,
which was code and mathematics.

I grew up in France,
and I also lived
in Switzerland and the U.K.

I liked the idea of
being flexible and not
having all the answers.

I think it just makes
things more exciting.

I leveraged CPD
resources a lot, I think.

I realized that there
were different resources

that I could access on
different parts of my journey.

There was this one
CPD coach who knew

so much about all of the
European tech industry
that I could go to.

And I spoke to him, and he
told me about so many startups
that I didn't even know.

I remember I came to
him, and I was like,

oh, I want to go back to
Europe, but no one does that.
There's nothing there.

Everything is in the U.S. And he
looked at me and was like, hmm,
are you sure?
And then I was in the tech club.

And I went to one of the tech
events, and speaking to ECs ECs
are also a great resource.

They've been through everything
that you've been through,

so the information
dump that you can

get from the ECs
is pretty valuable.

And one of them
was saying that she

worked with this CPD coach
who has experience in product
management, et cetera.

So I just went and
looked up that coach
and saw her a million hours.

And yeah, she really
walked me through

my whole interviewing
process, prepped me,
helped me revamp my resume.

I also leveraged all
the EC product managers

that do interview coaching
for product management.
So that was also super helpful.

Navigating a career
journey is a long game.

I don't think you
ever find the answer.

I think you just have to
get comfortable with making

decisions, making
mistakes, making attempts.
I could be wherever I want.

And what is the place that
has the winning combo for me?

And answering that question,
I think, took a little while.

But it became very clear to
me a year or so into the MBA

that being close to family
was something important,

and not sacrificing career
outcomes was something
that was important as well.

But people all have
different opinions.

And I think understanding
that their opinions are really

driven from different values
or really different preferences

and makes their decision
really difficult
to translate to another person.

When you come here,
there's so much
change that you go through.

There's so much
input and so many

new things that
you need to learn.

It's really hard to have
faith in the outcome

just because you
don't know nearly what
that outcome might look like.

But having faith in the
process and that all of this

is designed for you to
have an amazing time

and have amazing outcomes
when you come out of it,

I think trusting that was also
something that I wish someone
had told me to do on day one.
